tle’s Science of Matter and Motion’s focus is on refuting this misconception, arguing that Aristotle actually offered a systematic account of matter, motion, and the basic causal powers found in all physical objects. Author, Christopher Byrne sheds lights on Aristotle’s account of matter, revealing how Aristotle maintained that all perceptible objects are ultimately made from physical matter of one kind or another, accounting for their basic common features. For Aristotle, then, matter matters a great deal.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aMatter. 0aMotion. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018 Englishz978311060425208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018z9783110603255oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2018 Englishz978311060421408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2018z9783110603217oZDB-23-DPH08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z97831106067990 cprintz978148750396340uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148751916240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487519162423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781487519162/original  a978-3-11-060421-4  EBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2018 Englishb2018  a978-3-11-060425-2  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018 Englishb2018  a978-3-11-060679-9  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-DGGb2017  aZDB-23-DPHb2018